Reversible Reactions & Equilibrium

1. Reversible Reactions

Types of Reactions

(Tap to flip)

  • Completion Reactions: Reactants are used up to form products, and the reaction stops when reactants are gone.
  • Reversible Reactions: Product molecules can react or decompose to form the reactant molecules again. The reaction can occur in both directions!

Forward & Reverse Reactions

(Tap to flip)

  • Forward reaction: Reactants → Products
  • Reverse reaction: Products → Reactants
  • The symbol for a reversible reaction is ⇌.
  • Energy Rule: If the forward reaction is exothermic (releases heat), the reverse is endothermic (absorbs heat). The amount of heat transferred is identical for both directions.

Hydrated & Anhydrous Salts

(Tap to flip)

Hydrated salts contain water of crystallisation, which affects their molecular shape and colour.

Water of crystallisation: Water that is stoichiometrically included in the structure of some salts during their crystallisation process.

Example: Copper(II) Sulfate

CuSO₄·5H₂O ⇌ CuSO₄ + 5H₂O

Copper(II) Sulfate Details

(Tap to flip)

  • Hydrated Salt: Copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO₄·5H₂O). These are blue crystals.
  • Heating (Forward Reaction): Heating the blue crystals forms anhydrous copper(II) sulfate. This reaction is endothermic.
  • Anhydrous Salt: Copper(II) sulfate (CuSO₄). This is a white powder/crystal.
  • Adding Water (Reverse Reaction): Adding water to the white powder reforms the hydrated blue crystals. This reaction is highly exothermic.

Refer to your notes for the diagram of this reaction setup.

Cobalt(II) Chloride Details

(Tap to flip)

CoCl₂·6H₂O ⇌ CoCl₂ + 6H₂O

  • Hydrated Salt: Cobalt(II) chloride hexahydrate (CoCl₂·6H₂O). These are pink crystals.
  • Heating (Forward Reaction): Heating the pink crystals forms anhydrous cobalt(II) chloride. This reaction is endothermic.
  • Anhydrous Salt: Cobalt(II) chloride (CoCl₂). These are blue crystals.
  • Adding Water (Reverse Reaction): Adding water to the blue crystals reforms the hydrated pink crystals. This reaction is highly exothermic.

Refer to your notes for the diagram of this reaction setup.

Examiner's Tip: Test for Water

(Tap to flip)

Key Point!

The hydration of anhydrous CuSO₄ and CoCl₂ are chemical tests used to detect the presence of water.

Memorize these changes:

  • Anhydrous CoCl₂ (blue) + water → Hydrated CoCl₂ (pink)
  • Anhydrous CuSO₄ (white) + water → Hydrated CuSO₄ (blue)

2. Equilibrium (Extended Tier)

The Concept of Equilibrium

(Tap to flip)

Equilibrium can only be reached in a closed system (where no reactants or products can escape).

At equilibrium:

  • The rate of the forward reaction is equal to the rate of the reverse reaction.
  • The concentrations of reactants and products remain constant.
  • Equilibrium is dynamic – the reactions haven't stopped, they are just happening at the same rate.

Check your notes for the diagram comparing an open and closed system with iodine.

How Equilibrium is Reached

(Example: Haber Process)

  1. At the start, only N₂ and H₂ are present. The forward rate is at its highest.
  2. As the reaction proceeds, N₂ and H₂ concentrations decrease, so the forward rate slows down.
  3. Simultaneously, the concentration of NH₃ increases, so the reverse rate (decomposition of NH₃) speeds up.
  4. Eventually, the forward rate and reverse rate become equal. Equilibrium is reached!

The graph of reaction rate vs. time in your notes illustrates this perfectly.

Le Chatelier's Principle

The Golden Rule!

(Tap to flip)

"When a change is made to the conditions of a system at equilibrium, the system automatically moves to oppose the change."

The relative amounts of reactants and products at equilibrium depend on the conditions. We use this principle to predict how the equilibrium position will shift.

Shifting Equilibrium

(Tap to flip)

Key Definitions:

Shift to the right: The forward reaction is favoured, leading to an increase in the amount of products.

Shift to the left: The reverse reaction is favoured, leading to an increase in the amount of reactants.

Effect of Temperature

(Tap to flip)

The system tries to counteract the temperature change.

  • Increase Temperature: Equilibrium moves in the endothermic direction to absorb the extra heat.
  • Decrease Temperature: Equilibrium moves in the exothermic direction to release heat.

Effect of Pressure

(For reactions involving gases)

(Tap to flip)

The system tries to counteract the pressure change by shifting to the side with fewer/more gas molecules.

  • Increase Pressure: Equilibrium shifts in the direction that produces the least number of gas molecules.
  • Decrease Pressure: Equilibrium shifts in the direction that produces the greatest number of gas molecules.

Effect of Concentration

(Tap to flip)

The system tries to counteract the concentration change.

  • Increase concentration of a reactant: Shifts RIGHT to use it up.
  • Decrease concentration of a reactant: Shifts LEFT to make more of it.
  • Increase concentration of a product: Shifts LEFT to use it up.
  • Decrease concentration of a product: Shifts RIGHT to make more of it.

Effect of a Catalyst

(Tap to flip)

Catalysts have NO effect on the position of equilibrium.

They increase the rate of BOTH the forward and reverse reactions equally by providing an alternative pathway with a lower activation energy.

Result: Equilibrium is reached FASTER, but the final yield of products is identical. The concentration of reactants and products at equilibrium is the same as it would be without the catalyst.

Check your notes for the diagram showing this effect!

Examiner's Tip

(Tap to flip)

Remember this simple rule: when the conditions at equilibrium are changed, the system always responds by doing the OPPOSITE.

Visuals: Closed System, Rates & Catalyst

Effect of Pressure & Temperature on Ammonia Yield

Worked Examples: Applying the Principle

Example 1: ICl(dark brown) + Cl₂(yellow) ⇌ ICl₃ (Forward is exothermic)

What colour will the mixture turn when heated?

Answer: Increasing temperature favours the endothermic (reverse) reaction. The equilibrium will move to the left, producing more ICl and Cl₂. The mixture will become increasingly dark brown.

Example 2: 2NO₂(g) (brown) ⇌ N₂O₄(g) (colourless)

What will the colour change be if the pressure is increased?

Answer: The left side has 2 moles of gas; the right has 1 mole. Increasing pressure causes the equilibrium to shift to the side with fewer molecules (the right). More colourless N₂O₄ will be formed, so the mixture will become less brown/more colourless.

3. The Haber Process (Extended Tier)

This industrial process manufactures ammonia (NH₃) in an exothermic reaction.

N₂(g) + 3H₂(g) ⇌ 2NH₃(g)

Haber Process Flow Diagram

Remember to refer to the flow diagram of the Haber Process in your textbook to see how these stages connect!

Stage 1: Raw Materials: N₂ is obtained from the air, and H₂ from natural gas (methane). They are pumped into a compressor.
Stage 2: Compressor: Gases are compressed to around 20,000 kPa or 200 atmospheres.
Stage 3: Reactor Tank: Pressurised gases are passed over layers of an iron catalyst at a temperature of 450°C. Some N₂ and H₂ react to form NH₃.
Stage 4: Cooling Tank: The mixture of gases passes into a cooling tank. The ammonia liquefies and is removed to pressurised storage.
Stage 5: Recycling: Unreacted N₂ and H₂ gases are recycled back into the system to start over again.

Explaining the Conditions: The Great Compromise!

The chosen conditions are not ideal for maximum yield, but provide a balance between product yield, reaction rate, and production cost. This is a compromise.

Temperature: 450°C

A low temp gives a high yield (favours the exothermic forward reaction), but is VERY SLOW. A high temp is fast, but gives a low yield (favours the endothermic reverse reaction, decomposing NH₃). 450°C is a compromise between a reasonable rate and a decent yield.

Pressure: 200 atm

A high pressure gives a high yield (favours the side with fewer gas moles). However, maintaining very high pressures requires expensive equipment and can be dangerous. 200 atm is a compromise between a good yield and manageable cost/safety.

Catalyst: Iron

The iron catalyst doesn't change the yield, but it allows the reaction to reach equilibrium much faster. This allows an acceptable yield to be achieved at a lower temperature, making the whole process economically viable and saving costs.

Examiner's Tips

Examiners note that students often don't know where the nitrogen and hydrogen come from, or they confuse the iron catalyst with others (like vanadium oxide or enzymes).

You MUST know the raw materials and conditions: 200 atm, 450°C, and an iron catalyst.

4. The Contact Process (Extended Tier)

This process synthesises sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄), which is used in car batteries, making fertilisers, soaps, and detergents.

Stage 1: Make Sulfur Dioxide (SO₂): Oxygen from the air is used to oxidise sulfur. This is done by either burning sulfur (S + O₂ → SO₂) or roasting metal sulfide ores.

Stage 2: Make Sulfur Trioxide (SO₃) - The Key Reversible Step!

2SO₂(g) + O₂(g) ⇌ 2SO₃(g)

Conditions: A temperature of 450°C, a pressure of 2 atm (200 kPa), and a Vanadium(V) oxide (V₂O₅) catalyst. Oxygen is from the air.

Stage 3: Make Sulfuric Acid:
  1. The SO₃ is absorbed into concentrated 98% sulfuric acid to produce a thick liquid called oleum (H₂S₂O₇). This is done to avoid producing a fine, dangerous mist of sulfuric acid that is difficult to condense.
  2. The oleum is then safely diluted with water to form concentrated sulfuric acid (H₂O + H₂S₂O₇ → 2H₂SO₄).

Explaining the Conditions for Stage 2

Temperature: 450°C

Just like the Haber process, the forward reaction is exothermic. A low temperature gives a high yield but is very slow. 450°C is a compromise temperature for a good rate and yield.

Pressure: 2 atm

High pressure would favour the forward reaction (3 moles of gas → 2 moles). However, the position of equilibrium already lies far to the right (about 96% SO₃ yield). Therefore, a very high pressure isn't needed and would add unnecessary danger and cost. It could also cause the SO₂ to liquify. 2 atm is sufficient, cheaper, and safer.

Examiner's Tips

You need to be able to recall the temperature, pressure, catalyst, and the chemical equation for Stage 2 only.

Remember: The conditions for industrial processes are always a compromise between yield, rate, safety, and cost.
